## Problem Statement Selected
HR Cost Intelligence Engine

## Project Description
The HR Cost Intelligence Engine is an AI-powered tool that connects calendar meeting data to project budgets, giving organizations real-time visibility into how employee time and cost are distributed across projects.

It is built for finance teams, project managers, and leadership who currently have no automated way to see project-level HR expenditure — payroll is tracked as a whole, but cost-per-project is invisible and relies on unreliable manual timesheets.

The tool ingests meeting data (title, attendees, duration, recurrence), uses AI to infer which project each meeting belongs to, maps attendees to hourly cost rates, and aggregates this into a project-wise cost dashboard — flagging low-confidence or unusual cases for human review.

## Approach
The problem breaks down into four stages: data ingestion, AI-based project attribution, cost computation, and visualization.

For attribution, a hybrid approach is planned: first a fast rule-based keyword match against a project taxonomy (project name + keywords), and only for meetings with no clear match, a call to an LLM (Claude) that classifies the meeting into a project with a confidence score and reasoning, or marks it "Unassigned" if ambiguous.

This hybrid design keeps the system fast and cheap for clear-cut meetings while using AI specifically where it adds value — disambiguating vague titles like "Sync" or "1:1" using attendee and context signals.

Cost is computed per meeting by mapping each attendee's designation to a configurable hourly rate, then aggregated per project for the dashboard. Confidence scores and an "Unassigned" bucket are surfaced so low-confidence attributions can be reviewed rather than silently trusted — directly addressing the "graceful degradation" requirement in the problem statement.

## Tech Stack and Tools Used
Frontend: React, Vite, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, shadcn/ui, Recharts, React Query
Backend: Node.js, Express, TypeScript
Database: JSON file storage (planned; may move to SQLite/Postgres)
AI Tools/API: Claude (Anthropic API)
Cloud/Deployment: Vercel (frontend, planned), Render (backend, planned)
Other Tools: Turborepo (pnpm monorepo), Claude (used as coding assistant during development)

## Key Features
1. Calendar meeting data ingestion (mock dataset for prototype)
2. AI-powered project attribution using keyword rules + LLM classification with confidence scores
3. Employee-to-cost mapping based on configurable hourly rates
4. Project cost dashboard with bar chart and drill-down table by project/meeting
5. Anomaly flags for low-confidence attribution ("Needs Review") and high-cost meetings
6. "Unassigned" bucket for meetings with no clear project match

